FBIS4-57881 "drlat102_t_94007" FBIS-LAT-94-102 Daily Report 25 May 1994 Venezuela Finance Minister Expects Bolivar To Stabilize; To Visit U.S. Finance Minister Expects Bolivar To Stabilize; To Visit U.S. PA2605031894 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 25 May 94 PA2605031894 Caracas Union Radio Network Spanish BFN [From the "Union Radio News" newscast] [Text] Finance Minister Julio Sosa Rodriguez has said that within (?15) days the dollar exchange rate will stabilize at 150 bolivares because the U.S. currency is overvalued [passage indistinct]. [Begin Sosa recording] The exchange rate stands at 170 bolivares to the dollar. That is a completely overvalued dollar. The bolivar was overvalued in the past, but now we have an undervalued bolivar. I think nervousness led a number of people to apply pressure on a balance of payments that should have been perfectly manageable. They will probably realize in the future that the [words indistinct] was too good. [end recording] The finance minister reported that in a meeting today the Council of Ministers approved four tax laws [words indistinct], including a property tax [words indistinct], a tax on the sale of luxury items, and a wholesale tax. The wholesale tax will produce (?350) billion [currency not specified] for the national treasury [words indistinct]. Sosa announced that he will travel to Washington on Thursday to meet privately with IMF President Michel Camdessus to ask for help in restoring confidence in the country.
